data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_094ff417ea6814b80069a7e41e7690819586ed9bb97ec50dab","logprobs":[],"output_index":2,"sequence_number":506,"text":"Foundry Agent Service is Microsoft’s managed runtime in **Microsoft Foundry** for building, deploying, and operating **AI agents** in production. It’s designed to move beyond “chatbot demos” by providing the plumbing you typically need for real workflows: conversation/thread management, tool orchestration, safety controls, and integrations with enterprise Azure services. 【5:0†source】\n\n## What it does\n- **Runs and orchestrates agents**: connects an agent’s model + instructions + tools into a single execution runtime, and coordinates multi-step “runs” (e.g., decide → call tools → synthesize response). 【5:0†source】\n- **Manages conversations**: handles state like threads/messages so an agent can behave consistently over time. 【5:0†source】\n- **Tool calling & workflow automation**: lets agents use built-in and extensible tools to retrieve knowledge or take actions (e.g., web search/grounding, Azure AI Search, Logic Apps, OpenAPI tools, MCP endpoints, function calling, etc.). 【5:1†source】\n- **Trust, safety, and production readiness**: includes governance-oriented capabilities such as content safety and operational hooks so teams can deploy agents more safely and observe behavior in production. 【5:0†source】\n\n## How “tools” fit in (key concept)\nFoundry Agent Service supports adding optional **tools** that the model can choose to invoke based on user intent. Tools generally fall into:\n- **Knowledge tools** (ground responses in data sources like search/indexes)\n- **Action tools** (trigger workflows or call APIs) 【5:1†source】\n\n## Where “classic” vs “new” comes up\nMicrosoft’s docs distinguish a **classic agents API** and a newer experience/tooling in the Foundry portal. For example, “Grounding with Bing Search” and “Bing Custom Search” have classic versions, with guidance increasingly pointing to newer “Web Search tool”/tool catalog docs depending on the API you’re using. 【5:2†source】【5:3†source】\n\n## When you’d use it\nUse Foundry Agent Service when you want an agent that:\n- integrates with enterprise data/tools,\n- can take reliable actions (not just chat),\n- and needs deploy/operate features (safety, scaling patterns, observability hooks) rather than bespoke infrastructure. 【5:0†source】\n\nIf you tell me your scenario (e.g., IT helpdesk agent, invoice processing, internal knowledge assistant, customer support triage), I can map the typical Foundry Agent Service components/tools you’d pick."}

